dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: Let's talk about South Park, a popular American adult animated sitcom.

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: I love South Park! Cartman is my favorite character...what's yours?

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: I'm more of a Kyle fan, his reactions to Cartman's antics are priceless!

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: They really are a dynamic duo. Butters is another favorite of mine. What other characters do you like?

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: Kenny's muffled voice is hilarious, and I also enjoy the absurdity of some of the supporting characters, like Randy Marsh.

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: Randy is great. I love how in later seasons he really became a breakout character because he is so out there

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: His eccentricities and crazy schemes often provide some of the show's funniest moments!

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: Oh for sure. He was always good in the early seasons but when they cut him loose he really became hilarious like when he pretended to be the musician Lorde

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: That was a great episode! The show's creators, Trey Parker and Matt Stone, really know how to push the envelope with their characters and storylines.

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: Parker and Stone really do make some great stuff. I hear there will be another South Park movie at some point

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: Actually, South Park started as a couple of animated shorts, "The Spirit of Christmas", before becoming a TV show.

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: Oh I've seen it before. It was really creative how they really went with paper cutouts when making those shorts

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: That cutout style was even used in the first episode of the TV series, and later emulated with computer animation.

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: Yup. The technology caught up and they were able to implement that style easier which is how they are able to make an episode in a week or sometimes less. I love how they stay topical that way

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: It's impressive how they can produce episodes so quickly, and that's a big part of what keeps the show feeling fresh and relevant, even after all these years.

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: It's definitely shifted in some dynamics as a long running show should do, but SP has kept it essential to it's core while still moving forward which is why it still is on TV

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: And it's been renewed through 2019, so it's clear that Comedy Central still sees a lot of value in the show, even after two decades on the air.

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: I think it's now extended to 2030! something like that

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: I think you might be right, I've heard it's been renewed for a long time, but I don't have the exact date.

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: It's pretty exciting. Sometimes I won't watch for awhile but nearly 30 years later I still get drawn back in

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: South Park has a way of doing that, it's a show that can be taken in doses, but still remains appealing even after all these years.
